# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hydrochloric-acid-data-page
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] In optics and lens design, the **Abbe number**, also known as the **Vd-number** or **constringence** of a transparent material, is an approximate measure of a material's dispersion (change in refractive index as a function of wavelength), with high Vd values indicating low dispersion.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] It is named after Ernst Abbe (1840–1905), the German physicist who defined it.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] The term Vd-number should not be confused with the normalized frequency in fibers.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] This formulation only applies to human vision; outside this range, alternative spectral lines are required.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] For non-visible spectral lines, the term "V-number" is more commonly used.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] The more general formulation is $V\equiv {\frac {n_{\text{center}}-1}{n_{\text{short}}-n_{\text{long}}}},$ where $n_{\text{short}}$ , $n_{\text{center}}$ , and $n_{\text{long}}$ are the refractive indices of the material at three different wavelengths.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] Abbe numbers are used to classify glass and other optical materials in terms of their chromaticity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] For example, the higher dispersion flint glasses have relatively small Abbe numbers V less than 55, whereas the lower dispersion crown glasses have larger Abbe numbers.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] Values of $V_{\text{d}}$ range from below 25 for very dense flint glasses, around 34 for polycarbonate plastics, up to 65 for common crown glasses, and 75 to 85 for some fluorite and phosphate crown glasses.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] Abbe numbers are useful in the design of achromatic lenses, as their reciprocal is proportional to dispersion (slope of refractive index versus wavelength) in the domain where the human eye is most sensitive (see above figure).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] For other wavelength regions, or for higher precision in characterizing a system's chromaticity (such as in the design of apochromats), the full dispersion relation is used (i.e., refractive index as a function of wavelength).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] An **Abbe diagram** (sometimes referred to as "the glass veil") is produced by plotting the refractive index of a material $n_{\text{d}}$ as a function of Abbe number V .
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] Glasses can then be categorized and selected according to their positions on the diagram.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] This categorization could be in the form of a letter-number code, as used for example in the Schott Glass catalogue, or a 6-digit glass code.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] Glasses' Abbe numbers, along with their mean refractive indices, are used in the calculation of the required refractive powers of the elements of achromatic lenses in order to cancel chromatic aberration to first order.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] These two parameters, which enter into the equations for the design of achromatic doublets, are exactly what is plotted on an Abbe diagram.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] Due to the difficulty and inconvenience in producing sodium and hydrogen lines, alternate definitions of the Abbe number are often substituted (ISO 7944).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] Other definitions can be similarly employed; the following table lists standard wavelengths at which n is commonly determined, including the standard subscripts used.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/abbe-number] The difference in power can be expressed relative to the power at a center wavelength $\lambda _{\text{c}}$ : $P_{\text{c}}=(n_{\text{c}}-1)\left({\frac {1}{R_{1}}}-{\frac {1}{R_{2}}}\right),$ with $n_{\text{c}}$ having an analogous meaning as above.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometry influences several properties of a substance including its reactivity, polarity, phase of matter, color, magnetism and biological activity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The angles between bonds that an atom forms depend only weakly on the rest of a molecule, i.e. they can be understood as approximately local and hence transferable properties.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular geometry can be determined by various spectroscopic methods and diffraction methods.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] IR, microwave and Raman spectroscopy can give information about the molecule geometry from the details of the vibrational and rotational absorbance detected by these techniques.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] X-ray crystallography, neutron diffraction and electron diffraction can give molecular structure for crystalline solids based on the distance between nuclei and concentration of electron density.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Gas electron diffraction can be used for small molecules in the gas phase.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] NMR and FRET methods can be used to determine complementary information including relative distances, dihedral angles, angles, and connectivity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometries are best determined at low temperature because at higher temperatures the molecular structure is averaged over more accessible geometries (see next section).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Larger molecules often exist in multiple stable geometries (conformational isomerism) that are close in energy on the potential energy surface.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Geometries can also be computed by ab initio quantum chemistry methods to high accuracy.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular geometry can be different as a solid, in solution, and as a gas.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The position of each atom is determined by the nature of the chemical bonds by which it is connected to its neighboring atoms.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular geometry can be described by the positions of these atoms in space, evoking bond lengths of two joined atoms, bond angles of three connected atoms, and torsion angles (dihedral angles) of three consecutive bonds.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Since the motions of the atoms in a molecule are determined by quantum mechanics, "motion" must be defined in a quantum mechanical way.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The overall (external) quantum mechanical motions translation and rotation hardly change the geometry of the molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular vibrations are harmonic (at least to good approximation), and the atoms oscillate about their equilibrium positions, even at the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] At higher temperatures the vibrational modes may be thermally excited (in a classical interpretation one expresses this by stating that "the molecules will vibrate faster"), but they oscillate still around the recognizable geometry of the molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] To get a feeling for the probability that the vibration of molecule may be thermally excited, we inspect the Boltzmann factor *β* ≡ exp(−⁠Δ*E*/*kT*⁠), where Δ*E* is the excitation energy of the vibrational mode, *k* the Boltzmann constant and *T* the absolute temperature.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] (The reciprocal centimeter is an energy unit that is commonly used in infrared spectroscopy; 1 cm−1 corresponds to 1.23984×10−4 eV).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] When an excitation energy is 500 cm−1, then about 8.9 percent of the molecules are thermally excited at room temperature.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] To put this in perspective: the lowest excitation vibrational energy in water is the bending mode (about 1600 cm−1).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Thus, at room temperature less than 0.07 percent of all the molecules of a given amount of water will vibrate faster than at absolute zero.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] As stated above, rotation hardly influences the molecular geometry.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] But, as a quantum mechanical motion, it is thermally excited at relatively (as compared to vibration) low temperatures.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] From a classical point of view it can be stated that at higher temperatures more molecules will rotate faster, which implies that they have higher angular velocity and angular momentum.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] In quantum mechanical language: more eigenstates of higher angular momentum become thermally populated with rising temperatures.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Typical rotational excitation energies are on the order of a few cm−1.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The results of many spectroscopic experiments are broadened because they involve an averaging over rotational states.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] It is often difficult to extract geometries from spectra at high temperatures, because the number of rotational states probed in the experimental averaging increases with increasing temperature.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Thus, many spectroscopic observations can only be expected to yield reliable molecular geometries at temperatures close to absolute zero, because at higher temperatures too many higher rotational states are thermally populated.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Molecules, by definition, are most often held together with covalent bonds involving single, double, and/or triple bonds, where a "bond" is a shared pair of electrons (the other method of bonding between atoms is called ionic bonding and involves a positive cation and a negative anion).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometries can be specified in terms of 'bond lengths', 'bond angles' and 'torsional angles'.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The bond length is defined to be the average distance between the nuclei of two atoms bonded together in any given molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] A bond angle is the angle formed between three atoms across at least two bonds.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] For four atoms bonded together in a chain, the torsional angle is the angle between the plane formed by the first three atoms and the plane formed by the last three atoms.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] There exists a mathematical relationship among the bond angles for one central atom and four peripheral atoms (labeled 1 through 4) expressed by the following determinant.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] This constraint removes one degree of freedom from the choices of (originally) six free bond angles to leave only five choices of bond angles.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometry is determined by the quantum mechanical behavior of the electrons.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] Using the valence bond approximation this can be understood by the type of bonds between the atoms that make up the molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] When atoms interact to form a chemical bond, the atomic orbitals of each atom are said to combine in a process called orbital hybridisation.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The two most common types of bonds are sigma bonds (usually formed by hybrid orbitals) and pi bonds (formed by unhybridized p orbitals for atoms of main group elements).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The geometry can also be understood by molecular orbital theory where the electrons are delocalised.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] An understanding of the wavelike behavior of electrons in atoms and molecules is the subject of quantum chemistry.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] A bond angle is the geometric angle between two adjacent bonds.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The bond angles in the table below are ideal angles from the simple VSEPR theory, followed by the actual angle for the example given in the following column where this differs.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] For many cases, such as trigonal pyramidal and bent, the actual angle for the example differs from the ideal angle, and examples differ by different amounts.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] For example, the angle in H2S (92°) differs from the tetrahedral angle by much more than the angle for H2O (104.48°) does.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The greater the number of lone pairs contained in a molecule, the smaller the angles between the atoms of that molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-angle] The VSEPR theory predicts that lone pairs repel each other, thus pushing the different atoms away from them.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] In molecular geometry, **bond length** or **bond distance** is defined as the average distance between nuclei of two bonded atoms in a molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] It is a transferable property of a bond between atoms of fixed types, relatively independent of the rest of the molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Bond lengths are measured in the solid phase by means of X-ray diffraction, or approximated in the gas phase by microwave spectroscopy.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] A bond between a given pair of atoms may vary between different molecules.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] For example, the carbon to hydrogen bonds in methane are different from those in methyl chloride.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] It is however possible to make generalizations when the general structure is the same.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] A table with experimental single bonds for carbon to other elements is given below.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] By approximation the bond distance between two different atoms is the sum of the individual covalent radii (these are given in the chemical element articles for each element).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] As a general trend, bond distances *decrease* across the *row* in the periodic table and *increase* down a *group*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] This trend is identical to that of the atomic radius.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] The bond length between two atoms in a molecule depends not only on the atoms but also on such factors as the orbital hybridization and the electronic and steric nature of the substituents.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] The carbon–carbon (C–C) bond length in diamond is 154 pm.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] It is generally considered the average length for a carbon–carbon single bond, but is also the largest bond length that exists for ordinary carbon covalent bonds.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Since one atomic unit of length (i.e., a Bohr radius) is 52.9177 pm, the C–C bond length is 2.91 atomic units, or approximately three Bohr radii long.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Current record holder for the longest C-C bond with a length of 180.6 pm is 1,8-Bis(5-hydroxydibenzo[a,d]cycloheptatrien-5-yl)naphthalene, one of many molecules within a category of hexaaryl ethanes, which are derivatives based on hexaphenylethane skeleton.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Bond is located between carbons C1 and C2 as depicted in a picture below.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Another notable compound with an extraordinary C-C bond length is tricyclobutabenzene, in which a bond length of 160 pm is reported.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Longest C-C bond within the cyclobutabenzene category is 174 pm based on X-ray crystallography.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] In this type of compound the cyclobutane ring would force 90° angles on the carbon atoms connected to the benzene ring where they ordinarily have angles of 120°.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] The existence of a very long C–C bond length of up to 290 pm is claimed in a dimer of two tetracyanoethylene dianions, although this concerns a 2-electron-4-center bond.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] This type of bonding has also been observed in neutral phenalenyl dimers.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] The bond lengths of these so-called "pancake bonds" are up to 305 pm.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Shorter than average C–C bond distances are also possible: alkenes and alkynes have bond lengths of respectively 133 and 120 pm due to increased s-character of the sigma bond.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] In benzene all bonds have the same length: 139 pm.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Carbon–carbon single bonds increased s-character is also notable in the central bond of diacetylene (137 pm) and that of a certain tetrahedrane dimer (144 pm).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] In propionitrile the cyano group withdraws electrons, also resulting in a reduced bond length (144 pm).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Squeezing a C–C bond is also possible by application of strain.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] An unusual organic compound exists called In-methylcyclophane with a very short bond distance of 147 pm for the methyl group being squeezed between a triptycene and a phenyl group.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] In an in silico experiment a bond distance of 136 pm was estimated for neopentane locked up in fullerene.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] The smallest theoretical C–C single bond obtained in this study is 131 pm for a hypothetical tetrahedrane derivative.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] The same study also estimated that stretching or squeezing the C–C bond in an ethane molecule by 5 pm required 2.8 or 3.5 kJ/mol, respectively.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-length] Stretching or squeezing the same bond by 15 pm required an estimated 21.9 or 37.7 kJ/mol.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] In chemistry, **bond energy** (*BE*) is one measure of the strength of a chemical bond.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] It is sometimes called the **mean bond**, **bond enthalpy**, **average bond enthalpy**, or **bond strength**.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] IUPAC defines bond energy as the average value of the gas-phase bond-dissociation energy (usually at a temperature of 298.15 K) for all bonds of the same type within the same chemical species.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] The bond dissociation energy (enthalpy) is also referred to as bond disruption energy, bond energy, bond strength, or binding energy (abbreviation: *BDE*, *BE*, or *D*).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] It is defined as the standard enthalpy change of the following fission: R—*X* → R + *X*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] This equation tells us that the *BDE* for a given bond is equal to the energy of the individual components that make up the bond when they are free and unbonded minus the energy of the components when they are bonded together.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] These energies are given by the enthalpy of formation Δ*Hf*º of the components in each state.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] The enthalpy of formation of a large number of atoms, free radicals, ions, clusters and compounds is available from the websites of NIST, NASA, CODATA, and IUPAC.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Most authors use the *BDE* values at 298.15 K.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] For example, the carbon–hydrogen bond energy in methane *BE*(C–H) is the enthalpy change (∆*H*) of breaking one molecule of methane into a carbon atom and four hydrogen radicals, divided by four.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] The exact value for a certain pair of bonded elements varies somewhat depending on the specific molecule, so tabulated bond energies are generally averages from a number of selected typical chemical species containing that type of bond.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Bond energy (*BE*) is the average of all bond-dissociation energies of a single type of bond in a given molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] The bond-dissociation energies of several different bonds of the same type can vary even within a single molecule.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] For example, a water molecule is composed of two O–H bonds bonded as H–O–H.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Although the two bonds are the equivalent in the original symmetric molecule, the bond-dissociation energy of an oxygen–hydrogen bond varies slightly depending on whether or not there is another hydrogen atom bonded to the oxygen atom.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Thus, the bond energy of a molecule of water is 461.5 kJ/mol (110.3 kcal/mol).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] When the bond is broken, the bonding electron pair will split equally to the products.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] This process is called homolytic bond cleavage (homolytic cleavage; homolysis) and results in the formation of radicals.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] The strength of a bond can be estimated by comparing the atomic radii of the atoms that form the bond to the length of bond itself.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] For example, the atomic radius of boron is estimated at 85 pm, while the length of the B–B bond in Diboron tetrachloride, B2Cl4 is 175 pm.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] This ratio is slightly larger than 1, indicating that the bond itself is slightly longer than the expected minimum overlap between the two boron atoms' valence electron clouds.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Thus, we can conclude that this bond is a rather weak single bond.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] In another example, the atomic radius of rhenium is 135 pm, with a Re–Re bond length of 224 pm in the compound [Re2Cl8]−2.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] This ratio is notably lower than 1, indicating that there is a large amount of overlap between the valence electron clouds of the two rhenium atoms.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] From this data, we can conclude that this is a very strong bond.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Experimentally, the Re-Re bond in [Re2Cl8]−2 was found to be a quadruple bond.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] This method of determination is most useful for covalently bonded compounds.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] In ionic compounds, the electronegativity of the two atoms bonding together has a major effect on their bond energy.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] The extent of this effect is described by the compound's lattice energy, where a more negative lattice energy corresponds to a stronger force of attraction between the ions.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Generally, greater differences in electronegativity correspond to stronger ionic bonds.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] For example, the compound sodium chloride (NaCl) has a lattice energy of −786 kJ/mol with an electronegativity difference of 2.23 between sodium and chlorine.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/bond-strength] Meanwhile, the compound sodium iodide (NaI) has a lower lattice energy of −704 kJ/mol with a similarly lower electronegativity difference of 1.73 between sodium and iodine.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The **relative permittivity** (in older texts, **dielectric constant**) is the permittivity of a material expressed as a ratio with the electric permittivity of a vacuum.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] A dielectric is an insulating material, and the dielectric constant of an insulator measures the ability of the insulator to store electric energy in an electrical field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Permittivity is a material's property that affects the Coulomb force between two point charges in the material.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Relative permittivity is the factor by which the electric field between the charges is decreased relative to vacuum.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Likewise, relative permittivity is the ratio of the capacitance of a capacitor using that material as a dielectric, compared with a similar capacitor that has vacuum as its dielectric.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Relative permittivity is also commonly known as the dielectric constant, a term still used but deprecated by standards organizations in engineering as well as in chemistry.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] where *ε*(*ω*) is the complex frequency-dependent permittivity of the material, and *ε*0 is the vacuum permittivity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity of a medium is related to its electric susceptibility, *χ*e, as *ε*r(*ω*) = 1 + *χ*e.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] In anisotropic media (such as non cubic crystals) the relative permittivity is a second rank tensor.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity of a material for a frequency of zero is known as its **static relative permittivity**.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The historical term for the relative permittivity is *dielectric constant*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] It is still commonly used, but has been deprecated by standards organizations, because of its ambiguity, as some older reports used it for the absolute permittivity *ε*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The permittivity may be quoted either as a static property or as a frequency-dependent variant, in which case it is also known as the *dielectric function*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] It has also been used to refer to only the real component *ε*′r of the complex-valued relative permittivity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the causal theory of waves, permittivity is a complex quantity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The imaginary part corresponds to a phase shift of the polarization **P** relative to **E** and leads to the attenuation of electromagnetic waves passing through the medium.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] By definition, the linear relative permittivity of vacuum is equal to 1, that is *ε* = *ε*0, although there are theoretical nonlinear quantum effects in vacuum that become non-negligible at high field strengths.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The following table gives some typical values.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative low frequency permittivity of ice is ~96 at −10.8 °C, falling to 3.15 at high frequency, which is independent of temperature.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] It remains in the range 3.12–3.19 for frequencies between about 1 MHz and the far infrared region.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative static permittivity, *ε*r, can be determined for static electric fields as follows: first the capacitance of a test capacitor, *C*0, is measured with vacuum between its plates.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Then, using the same capacitor and distance between its plates, the capacitance *C* with a dielectric between the plates is measured.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] For time-variant electromagnetic fields, this quantity becomes frequency-dependent.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] An indirect technique to calculate *ε*r is conversion of radio frequency S-parameter measurement results.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] A description of frequently used S-parameter conversions for determination of the frequency-dependent *ε*r of dielectrics can be found in this bibliographic source.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Alternatively, resonance based effects may be employed at fixed frequencies.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity is an essential piece of information when designing capacitors, and in other circumstances where a material might be expected to introduce capacitance into a circuit.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] If a material with a high relative permittivity is placed in an electric field, the magnitude of that field will be measurably reduced within the volume of the dielectric.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] This fact is commonly used to increase the capacitance of a particular capacitor design.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The layers beneath etched conductors in printed circuit boards (PCBs) also act as dielectrics.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Dielectrics are used in radio frequency (RF) transmission lines.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] In a coaxial cable, polyethylene can be used between the center conductor and outside shield.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] It can also be placed inside waveguides to form filters.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Optical fibers are examples of *dielectric waveguides*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] They consist of dielectric materials that are purposely doped with impurities so as to control the precise value of *ε*r within the cross-section.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] This controls the refractive index of the material and therefore also the optical modes of transmission.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] However, in these cases it is technically the relative permittivity that matters, as they are not operated in the electrostatic limit.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative permittivity of air changes with temperature, humidity, and barometric pressure.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Sensors can be constructed to detect changes in capacitance caused by changes in the relative permittivity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Most of this change is due to effects of temperature and humidity as the barometric pressure is fairly stable.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Using the capacitance change, along with the measured temperature, the relative humidity can be obtained using engineering formulas.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The relative static permittivity of a solvent is a relative measure of its chemical polarity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] For example, water is very polar, and has a relative static permittivity of 80.10 at 20 °C while *n*-hexane is non-polar, and has a relative static permittivity of 1.89 at 20 °C.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] This information is important when designing separation, sample preparation and chromatography techniques in analytical chemistry.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The correlation should, however, be treated with caution.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] For instance, dichloromethane has a value of *ε*r of 9.08 (20 °C) and is rather poorly soluble in water (13 g/L or 9.8 mL/L at 20 °C); at the same time, tetrahydrofuran has its *ε*r = 7.52 at 22 °C, but it is completely miscible with water.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the case of tetrahydrofuran, the oxygen atom can act as a hydrogen bond acceptor; whereas dichloromethane cannot form hydrogen bonds with water.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] This is even more remarkable when comparing the *ε*r values of acetic acid (6.2528) and that of iodoethane (7.6177).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] The large numerical value of *ε*r is not surprising in the second case, as the iodine atom is easily polarizable; nevertheless, this does not imply that it is polar, too (electronic polarizability prevails over the orientational one in this case).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] where *λ* is the wavelength, *c* is the speed of light in vacuum and *κ* = *μ*0*c* / 2π = 59.95849 Ω ≈ 60.0 Ω is a newly introduced constant (units ohms, or reciprocal siemens, such that *σλκ* = *ε*r remains unitless).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] Permittivity is typically associated with dielectric materials, however metals are described as having an effective permittivity, ${\tilde {\epsilon }}=\epsilon +i{\frac {\sigma }{\omega }}$ , with real relative permittivity equal to one, ( $\epsilon _{r}=1$ ).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the high-frequency region, which extends from radio frequencies to the far infrared and terahertz region, the plasma frequency of the electron gas is much greater than the electromagnetic propagation frequency, so the refractive index *n* of a metal is very nearly a purely imaginary number.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/dielectric-constant] In the low frequency regime, the effective relative permittivity is also almost purely imaginary: It has a very large imaginary value related to the conductivity and a comparatively insignificant real-value.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid-data-page] This page provides supplementary chemical data on Hydrochloric acid.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid-data-page] The handling of this chemical may incur notable safety precautions.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid-data-page] It is highly recommend that you seek the Material Safety Datasheet (MSDS) for this chemical from a reliable source and follow its directions.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Because it was produced from rock salt according to the methods of Johann Rudolph Glauber, hydrochloric acid was historically called by European alchemists *spirits of salt* or *acidum salis* (salt acid).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Both names are still used, especially in other languages, such as for example German: *Salzsäure*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Gaseous HCl was called *marine acid air*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The name *muriatic acid* has the same origin (*muriatic* means "pertaining to brine or salt", hence *muriate* means hydrochloride), and this name is still sometimes used.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The name *hydrochloric acid* was coined by the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac in 1814.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In the early tenth century, the Persian physician and alchemist Abu Bakr al-Razi (c.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] 865–925, Latin: Rhazes) conducted experiments with sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride) and vitriol (hydrated sulfates of various metals), which he distilled together, thus producing the gas hydrogen chloride.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] However, it appears that in most of his experiments al-Razi disregarded the gaseous products, concentrating instead on the color changes that could be effected in the residue.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Multhauf, hydrogen chloride was produced many times without clear recognition that, by dissolving it in water, hydrochloric acid may be produced.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In this process, hydrochloric acid actually started to form, but it immediately reacted with the mercury to produce corrosive sublimate.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] One important invention that resulted from the discovery of the mineral acids is *aqua regia*, a mixture of nitric acid and hydrochloric acid in a 1:3 proportion, capable of dissolving gold.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] This was first described in pseudo-Geber's *De inventione veritatis* ("On the Discovery of Truth", after c.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] 1300), where *aqua regia* was prepared by adding ammonium chloride to nitric acid.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The fact that *aqua regia* typically is defined as a mixture of nitric acid and hydrochloric acid does not mean that hydrochloric acid was discovered before or simultaneously with *aqua regia*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The isolation of hydrochloric acid happened about 300 years later.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The production of hydrochloric acid itself (i.e., as an isolated substance rather than as already mixed with nitric acid) depended on the use of more efficient cooling apparatus, which would only develop in subsequent centuries.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] From the point of view of Western history of chemistry, hydrochloric acid was the last of the three well-known mineral acids for which the method of its production appeared in the literature.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Recipes for its production started to appear in the late sixteenth century.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The earliest recipes for the production of hydrochloric acid are found in Giovanni Battista Della Porta's (1535–1615) *Magiae naturalis* ("Natural Magic") and in the works of other contemporary chemists like Andreas Libavius (c.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] — Ladislao Reti, How Old Is Hydrochloric Acid?
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The knowledge of mineral acids such as hydrochloric acid would be of key importance to seventeenth-century chemists like Daniel Sennert (1572–1637) and Robert Boyle (1627–1691), who used their capability to rapidly dissolve metals in their demonstrations of the composite nature of bodies.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] During the Industrial Revolution in Europe, demand for alkaline substances increased.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] A new industrial process developed by Nicolas Leblanc of Issoudun, France enabled inexpensive large-scale production of sodium carbonate (soda ash).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In this Leblanc process, common salt is converted to soda ash, using sulfuric acid, limestone, and coal, releasing hydrogen chloride as a by-product.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Until the British Alkali Act 1863 and similar legislation in other countries, the excess HCl was often vented into the air.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] An early exception was the Bonnington Chemical Works, where, in 1830, the HCl began to be captured and the hydrochloric acid produced was used in making sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] After the passage of the act, soda ash producers were obliged to absorb the waste gas in water, producing hydrochloric acid on an industrial scale.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In the 20th century, the Leblanc process was effectively replaced by the Solvay process without a hydrochloric acid by-product.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Since hydrochloric acid was already fully settled as an important chemical in numerous applications, the commercial interest initiated other production methods, some of which are still used today.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Since 2000, hydrochloric acid is mostly made by absorbing by-product hydrogen chloride from industrial organic compounds production.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Gaseous hydrogen chloride is a molecular compound with a covalent bond between the hydrogen and chlorine atoms.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In aqueous solutions dissociation is complete, with the formation of chloride ions and hydrated hydrogen ions (hydronium ions).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] A combined IR, Raman, X-ray, and neutron diffraction study of concentrated hydrochloric acid showed that the hydronium ion forms hydrogen bonded complexes with other water molecules.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The p*K*a value of hydrochloric acid in aqueous solution is estimated theoretically to be −5.9.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] A solution of hydrogen chloride in water behaves as a strong acid: the concentration of HCl molecules is effectively zero.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] and refer to the total vapor pressure of the solution.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Physical properties of hydrochloric acid, such as boiling and melting points, density, and pH, depend on the concentration or molarity of HCl in the aqueous solution.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] They range from those of water at very low concentrations approaching 0% HCl to values for fuming hydrochloric acid at over 40% HCl.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid as the binary (two-component) mixture of HCl and H2O has a constant-boiling azeotrope at 20.2% HCl and 108.6 °C (381.8 K; 227.5 °F).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] There are four constant-crystallization eutectic points for hydrochloric acid, between the crystal form of [H3O]Cl (68% HCl), [H5O2]Cl (51% HCl), [H7O3]Cl (41% HCl), [H3O]Cl·5H2O (25% HCl), and ice (0% HCl).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] There is also a metastable eutectic point at 24.8% between ice and the [H7O3]Cl crystallization.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid is usually prepared industrially by dissolving hydrogen chloride in water.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrogen chloride can be generated in many ways, so several precursors to hydrochloric acid exist.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The large-scale production of hydrochloric acid is almost always integrated with the industrial scale production of other chemicals, such as in the chloralkali process which produces hydroxide, hydrogen, and chlorine, the latter of which can be combined to produce HCl.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] As the reaction is exothermic, the installation is called an HCl oven or HCl burner.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The resulting hydrogen chloride gas is absorbed in deionized water, resulting in chemically pure hydrochloric acid.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] This reaction can give a very pure product, e.g. for use in the food industry.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid is produced in solutions up to 38% HCl (concentrated grade).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Higher concentrations up to just over 40% are chemically possible, but the evaporation rate is then so high that storage and handling require extra precautions, such as pressurization and cooling.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Bulk industrial-grade is therefore 30% to 35%, optimized to balance transport efficiency and product loss through evaporation.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In the United States, solutions of between 20% and 32% are sold as muriatic acid.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Solutions for household purposes in the US, mostly cleaning, are typically 10% to 12%, with strong recommendations to dilute before use.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In the United Kingdom, where it is sold as "Spirits of Salt" for domestic cleaning, the potency is the same as the US industrial grade.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In other countries, such as Italy, hydrochloric acid for domestic or industrial cleaning is sold as "Acido Muriatico", and its concentration ranges from 5% to 32%.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Major producers worldwide include Dow Chemical at 2 million tonnes annually (Mt/year), calculated as HCl gas, Georgia Gulf Corporation, Tosoh Corporation, Akzo Nobel, and Tessenderlo at 0.5 to 1.5 Mt/year each.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Total world production, for comparison purposes expressed as HCl, is estimated at 20 Mt/year, with 3 Mt/year from direct synthesis, and the rest as secondary product from organic and similar syntheses.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] By far, most hydrochloric acid is consumed captively by the producer.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The open world market size is estimated at 5 Mt/year.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid is a strong inorganic acid that is used in many industrial processes such as refining metal.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The application often determines the required product quality.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrogen chloride, not hydrochloric acid, is used more widely in industrial organic chemistry, e.g. for vinyl chloride and dichloroethane.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] One of the most important applications of hydrochloric acid is in the pickling of steel, to remove rust or iron oxide scale from iron or steel before subsequent processing, such as extrusion, rolling, galvanizing, and other techniques.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Technical quality HCl at typically 18% concentration is the most commonly used pickling agent for the pickling of carbon steel grades.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The spent acid has long been reused as iron(II) chloride (also known as ferrous chloride) solutions, but high heavy-metal levels in the pickling liquor have decreased this practice.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The steel pickling industry has developed hydrochloric acid regeneration processes, such as the spray roaster or the fluidized bed HCl regeneration process, which allow the recovery of HCl from spent pickling liquor.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] By recuperation of the spent acid, a closed acid loop is established.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The iron(III) oxide by-product of the regeneration process is valuable, used in a variety of secondary industries.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Akin to its use for pickling, hydrochloric acid is used to dissolve many metals, metal oxides and metal carbonates.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] These processes are used to produce metal chlorides for analysis or further production.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid can be used to regulate the acidity (pH) of solutions.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In industry demanding purity (food, pharmaceutical, drinking water), high-quality hydrochloric acid is used to control the pH of process water streams.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] In less-demanding industry, technical quality hydrochloric acid suffices for neutralizing waste streams and swimming pool pH control.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] High-quality hydrochloric acid is used in the regeneration of ion exchange resins.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Cation exchange is widely used to remove ions such as Na+ and Ca2+ from aqueous solutions, producing demineralized water.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The acid is used to rinse the cations from the resins.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Na+ is replaced with H+ and Ca2+ with 2 H+.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Ion exchangers and demineralized water are used in all chemical industries, drinking water production, and many food industries.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Of the common strong mineral acids in chemistry, hydrochloric acid is the monoprotic acid least likely to undergo an interfering oxidation-reduction reaction.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] It is one of the least hazardous strong acids to handle; despite its acidity, it contains the non-reactive and non-toxic chloride ion.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Intermediate-strength hydrochloric acid solutions are quite stable upon storage, maintaining their concentrations over time.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] These attributes, plus the fact that it is available as a pure reagent, make hydrochloric acid an excellent acidifying reagent.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid is the preferred acid in titration for determining the amount of bases.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Strong acid titrants give more precise results due to a more distinct endpoint.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Azeotropic, or "constant-boiling", hydrochloric acid (roughly 20.2%) can be used as a primary standard in quantitative analysis, although its exact concentration depends on the atmospheric pressure when it is prepared.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid is used for a large number of small-scale applications, such as leather processing, household cleaning, and building construction.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Oil production may be stimulated by injecting hydrochloric acid into the rock formation of an oil well, dissolving a portion of the rock, and creating a large-pore structure.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Oil well acidizing is a common process in the North Sea oil production industry.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid has been used for dissolving calcium carbonate, e.g. such things as de-scaling kettles and for cleaning mortar off brickwork.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Many chemical reactions involving hydrochloric acid are applied in the production of food, food ingredients, and food additives.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Typical products include aspartame, fructose, citric acid, lysine, hydrolyzed vegetable protein as food enhancer, and in gelatin production.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Food-grade (extra-pure) hydrochloric acid can be applied when needed for the final product.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Gastric acid is one of the main secretions of the stomach.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] It consists mainly of hydrochloric acid and acidifies the stomach content to a pH of 1 to 2.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Chloride (Cl−) and hydrogen (H+) ions are secreted separately in the stomach fundus region at the top of the stomach by parietal cells of the gastric mucosa into a secretory network called canaliculi before it enters the stomach lumen.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Gastric acid acts as a barrier against microorganisms to prevent infections and is important for the digestion of food.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Its low pH denatures proteins and thereby makes them susceptible to degradation by digestive enzymes such as pepsin.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The low pH also activates the enzyme precursor pepsinogen into the active enzyme pepsin by self-cleavage.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] After leaving the stomach, the hydrochloric acid of the chyme is neutralized in the duodenum by bicarbonate.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] The stomach itself is protected from the strong acid by the secretion of a thick mucus layer, and by secretin induced buffering with sodium bicarbonate.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Heartburn or peptic ulcers can develop when these mechanisms fail.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Drugs of the antihistaminic and proton pump inhibitor classes can inhibit the production of acid in the stomach, and antacids are used to neutralize excessive existing acid.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid is also used by osteoclasts alongside proteases for bone resorption.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Being a strong acid, hydrochloric acid is corrosive to living tissue and to many materials, but not to rubber.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Typically, rubber protective gloves and related protective gear are used when handling concentrated solutions.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Vapors or mists are a respiratory hazard, which can be partially mitigated by use of a respirator equipped with cartridges specifically designed to capture hydrochloric acid.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Airborne acid is an irritant to the eyes, and may require the use of protective goggles or a facemask.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/hydrochloric-acid] Hydrochloric acid has been listed as a Table II precursor under the 1988 United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances because of its use in the production of heroin, cocaine, and methamphetamine.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In electromagnetism, the **magnetic susceptibility** (from Latin *susceptibilis* 'receptive'; denoted χ, chi) is a measure of how much a material will become magnetized in an applied magnetic field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] It is the ratio of magnetization **M** (magnetic moment per unit volume) to the applied magnetic field intensity **H**.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] This allows a simple classification, into two categories, of most materials' responses to an applied magnetic field: an alignment with the magnetic field, *χ* > 0, called paramagnetism, or an alignment against the field, *χ* < 0, called diamagnetism.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Magnetic susceptibility indicates whether a material is attracted into or repelled out of a magnetic field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Paramagnetic materials align with the applied field and are attracted to regions of greater magnetic field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Diamagnetic materials are anti-aligned and are pushed away, toward regions of lower magnetic fields.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] On top of the applied field, the magnetization of the material adds its own magnetic field, causing the field lines to concentrate in paramagnetism, or be excluded in diamagnetism.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Quantitative measures of the magnetic susceptibility also provide insights into the structure of materials, providing insight into bonding and energy levels.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Furthermore, it is widely used in geology for paleomagnetic studies and structural geology.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The magnetizability of materials comes from the atomic-level magnetic properties of the particles of which they are made.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Usually, this is dominated by the magnetic moments of electrons.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Electrons are present in all materials, but without any external magnetic field, the magnetic moments of the electrons are usually either paired up or random so that the overall magnetism is zero (the exception to this usual case is ferromagnetism).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The fundamental reasons why the magnetic moments of the electrons line up or do not are very complex and cannot be explained by classical physics.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] However, a useful simplification is to measure the magnetic susceptibility of a material and apply the macroscopic form of Maxwell's equations.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] This allows classical physics to make useful predictions while avoiding the underlying quantum mechanical details.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Magnetic susceptibility is a dimensionless proportionality constant that indicates the degree of magnetization of a material in response to an applied magnetic field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] A related term is **magnetizability**, the proportion between magnetic moment and (vacuum) magnetic field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] A closely related parameter is the permeability, which expresses the total magnetization of material and volume.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] This allows an alternative description of all magnetization phenomena in terms of the quantities **I** and **B**, as opposed to the commonly used **M** and **H**.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The definitions above are according to the International System of Quantities (ISQ) upon which the SI is based.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] However, many tables of magnetic susceptibility give the values of the corresponding quantities of the CGS system (more specifically CGS-EMU, short for electromagnetic units, or Gaussian-CGS; both are the same in this context).
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] For example, the CGS volume magnetic susceptibility of water at 20 °C is 7.19×10−7, which is 9.04×10−6 using the SI convention, both quantities being dimensionless.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Whereas for most electromagnetic quantities, which system of quantities it belongs to can be disambiguated by incompatibility of their units, this is not true for the susceptibility quantities.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In physics it is common to see CGS mass susceptibility with unit cm3/g or emu/g⋅Oe−1, and the CGS molar susceptibility with unit cm3/mol or emu/mol⋅Oe−1.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] If *χ* is positive, a material can be paramagnetic.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In this case, the magnetic field in the material is strengthened by the induced magnetization.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Alternatively, if *χ* is negative, the material is diamagnetic.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In this case, the magnetic field in the material is weakened by the induced magnetization.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Generally, nonmagnetic materials are said to be para- or diamagnetic because they do not possess permanent magnetization without external magnetic field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Ferromagnetic, ferrimagnetic, or antiferromagnetic materials possess permanent magnetization even without external magnetic field and do not have a well defined zero-field susceptibility.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Volume magnetic susceptibility is measured by the force change felt upon a substance when a magnetic field gradient is applied.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Early measurements are made using the Gouy balance where a sample is hung between the poles of an electromagnet.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The change in weight when the electromagnet is turned on is proportional to the susceptibility.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Today, high-end measurement systems use a superconductive magnet.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] An alternative is to measure the force change on a strong compact magnet upon insertion of the sample.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] This system, widely used today, is called the Evans balance.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] For liquid samples, the susceptibility can be measured from the dependence of the NMR frequency of the sample on its shape or orientation.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Another method using NMR techniques measures the magnetic field distortion around a sample immersed in water inside an MR scanner.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] This method is highly accurate for diamagnetic materials with susceptibilities similar to water.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The magnetic susceptibility of most crystals is not a scalar quantity.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Magnetic response **M** is dependent upon the orientation of the sample and can occur in directions other than that of the applied field **H**.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In these cases, volume susceptibility is defined as a tensor: $M_{i}=H_{j}\chi _{ij}$ where i and j refer to the directions (e.g., of the x and y Cartesian coordinates) of the applied field and magnetization, respectively.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The tensor is thus degree 2 (second order), dimension (3,3) describing the component of magnetization in the ith direction from the external field applied in the jth direction.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In ferromagnetic crystals, the relationship between **M** and **H** is not linear.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] To accommodate this, a more general definition of *differential susceptibility* is used: $\chi _{ij}^{d}={\frac {\partial M_{i}}{\partial H_{j}}}$ where *χ**d* *ij* is a tensor derived from partial derivatives of components of **M** with respect to components of **H**.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] When the coercivity of the material parallel to an applied field is the smaller of the two, the differential susceptibility is a function of the applied field and self interactions, such as the magnetic anisotropy.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] When the material is not saturated, the effect will be nonlinear and dependent upon the domain wall configuration of the material.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Several experimental techniques allow for the measurement of the electronic properties of a material.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] An important effect in metals under strong magnetic fields, is the oscillation of the differential susceptibility as function of ⁠1/*H*⁠.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] This behaviour is known as the De Haas–Van Alphen effect and relates the period of the susceptibility with the Fermi surface of the material.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] An analogue non-linear relation between magnetization and magnetic field happens for antiferromagnetic materials.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] When the magnetic susceptibility is measured in response to an AC magnetic field (i.e. a magnetic field that varies sinusoidally), this is called *AC susceptibility*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] AC susceptibility (and the closely related "AC permeability") are complex number quantities, and various phenomena, such as resonance, can be seen in AC susceptibility that cannot occur in constant-field (DC) susceptibility.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In particular, when an AC field is applied perpendicular to the detection direction (called the "transverse susceptibility" regardless of the frequency), the effect has a peak at the ferromagnetic resonance frequency of the material with a given static applied field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Currently, this effect is called the *microwave permeability* or *network ferromagnetic resonance* in the literature.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] These results are sensitive to the domain wall configuration of the material and eddy currents.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In terms of ferromagnetic resonance, the effect of an AC-field applied along the direction of the magnetization is called *parallel pumping*.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics has one of the few published magnetic susceptibility tables.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] The molar susceptibility of several elements and compounds are listed in the CRC.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Another compilation of magnetic susceptibility data is published in Tables of Physical Values (Таблицы физических величин), 1976.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In Earth science, magnetism is a useful parameter to describe and analyze rocks.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Additionally, the anisotropy of magnetic susceptibility (AMS) within a sample determines parameters as directions of paleocurrents, maturity of paleosol, flow direction of magma injection, tectonic strain, etc.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] It is a non-destructive tool which quantifies the average alignment and orientation of magnetic particles within a sample.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In oil exploration, magnetic susceptibility can determine prospective hydrocarbon deposites.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In 2014, a research conducted in western Ukraine revealed that prospective hydrocarbon deposit locations presented higher values of mass-specific magnetic susceptibility that was calculated in laboratory from rock samples obtained on field.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Moreover, magnetic susceptibility can distinguish crude oil from different worldwide oil reservoir.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Measuring magnetic susceptibility, it is possible to quantify clay content in clastic shoreface reservoir; minerals as illite and quartz can be measured through mass magnetic susceptibility, high amounts of these components are highly correlated with the presence of clay contents into the reservoir.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Final results show that magnetic susceptibility measurements have good correspondences compared with traditional methods of measuring minerals in rocks as gamma ray and XDR.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Furthermore, magnetic susceptibility can characterize permeability of reservoir rock.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] Comparing low field and high field magnetic susceptibility measurements, in the high ones exists a higher correlation between the magnetic susceptibility and the permeability of the reservoir.
[src:hydrochloric-acid-data-page/magnetic-susceptibility] In a shoreface North Sea oil reservoir was observed a slightly higher correlation with permeability in high field susceptibility (Potter and Ivakhnenko, 2008), and a much higher correlation with permeability and porosity in an Arab-D carbonate reservoir (Potter et al., 2011).
